			<div class="article-correspondence layout-item fill-pattern-light">
		<div class="layout-item-intro">
			<h2>Correspondence</h2>
			<a class="xsmall link-alt" href="https://www.thesunmagazine.org/letter-to-the-editor">Write a Letter to the Editor&nbsp;&#9656;</a>
		</div>

		<div id="article-correspondences" class="correspondences correspondences-collapsed">
								<div class="block-correspondence" id="1942">
		<blockquote class="quote-2">
			<p>Genie Zeiger&rsquo;s account of having rhinoplasty as a young woman [&ldquo;<a href="/article/2193">My Nose</a>,&rdquo; June 2003] both delighted and angered me. I was delighted to see that no one ever took a scalpel to Zeiger&rsquo;s sense of humor, but angered by the fact that she felt the need to have a nose job. In what I assume is a &ldquo;before&rdquo; photo, her face has dignity and character. In the era that Zeiger grew up in, however, a woman&rsquo;s face was not supposed to have character. It was supposed to look cute.</p>

<p>I would think that the post-feminist women of today would have better sense than to undergo such a procedure, but Jewish women are still bobbing their noses and otherwise surgically altering their bodies to appear more attractive.</p>
							<p class="quote-2-author">Silvia S. Crockett<br>San Antonio, Texas</p>
					</blockquote>
	</div>

					</div>

			</div>
    
